-- PRESS DIGEST-New Zealand newspapers - Aug 1
-- 
-- Thu Jul 31, 2014 03:49PM EDT
-- None



WELLINGTON, Aug 1 (Reuters) - Following are some of the lead stories from New Zealand metropolitan newspapers on Friday.

Stories may be taken from either the paper or Internet editions of the papers. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.  DOMINION POST(www.stuff.co.nz) Poll rebound offers Labour a glimpse: A new poll has breathed life into Labour's hopes of an upset win, just as Parliament rose for the final time before the election. - - - - Property market cooling: Residential land developer CDL Investments New Zealand <CDI.NZ> says its first half-year sales and profit were "satisfactory", but believes the property market is showing signs of softening. - - - - Profit helps extend life of Reefton mine a tad: The life of the Reefton gold mine will be "slightly" extended, OceanaGold <OGC.AX> says, as it reported a US$56.8 million (NZ$66.7m) profit for the half year, a turnaround from the previous half year's loss. - - - - Pateke, Oi exploration wells blow budget: One of the partners in the offshore Taranaki Tui field has revealed a cost blowout in drilling wells at Pateke and Oi recently, with total costs of about US$162 million for all the partners. - - - -   NEW ZEALAND HERALD (www.nzherald.co.nz) Telecom TV fuels channel battle: New Zealanders now have more television viewing options at lower prices, as internet TV services start and existing platforms react to protect their territory.  Telecom's <TEL.NZ> internet television venture, Lightbox, was launched in beta (testing) mode yesterday, offering a raft of high-profile on-demand shows for $15 a month. - - - - Start taxing property gains properly, says economist: NZIER's principal economist Shamubeel Eaqub wants capital gains tax collection on residential rental properties enforced more rigorously and has called for a more equitable system which doesn't inherently favour housing investment. - - - -